    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-20T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="355"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/11740: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HLW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-20T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 20, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 20—11:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>332. The Soviet press announces today the sentencing by the Military Collegium of
                    the Supreme Court and the execution of seven prominent Party or State officials
                    including <persName>Enukidze</persName>, formerly member of the Central
                    Committee of the Party, and Secretary of the Central <pb facs="0507" n="401"
                        xml:id="pg_401"/> Executive Committee; <persName corresp="#p_KLM2"
                        >Karakhan</persName>, formerly Ambassador to China and Turkey as well as
                    Assistant Commissar for Foreign Affairs; <persName corresp="#p_TVM1"
                        >Tsukerman</persName>, until recently Chief of Division of the Foreign
                    Office handling Near Eastern Affairs; and <persName corresp="#p_SBS1">Boris
                        Steiger</persName>, for many years non-Foreign Office contact man between
                    the Soviet Government and the Diplomatic Corps.</p>
                <p>All have been accused of “betraying their country, terrorist activities and
                    systematic espionage on behalf of a certain foreign power” and to have pleaded
                    guilty.</p>
                <p>According to the press some of them have been charged with crimes of a more
                    specific nature. <persName corresp="#p_KLM2">Karakhan</persName>, for instance,
                    of having sold “to Fascist intelligence circles secrets of exceptional State
                    importance”; <persName corresp="#p_SBS1">Steiger</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_TVM1">Tsukerman</persName> of having “sold information to
                    intelligence circles of a certain foreign power”; <persName corresp="#p_SBS1"
                        >Steiger</persName> of having “carried on active espionage work since 1918”;
                    and <persName>Enukidze</persName> of having been connected with “the general
                    staff of a certain Fascist country.” With respect to <persName corresp="#p_SBS1"
                        >Steiger</persName> please see my despatch number 249 of April 28,
                        1937.<note n="51" xml:id="d355fn51">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HLW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
